          "body": "The treatment of suspected idolatry (vv.4–7) is remarkable for its procedural safeguards. The allegation must be reported (17:4), investigated thoroughly (*darash*, to inquire diligently), and confirmed as true and certain before any judgment falls. Capital punishment requires two or three witnesses (17:6) — a principle the New Testament inherits and applies to church discipline (Matthew 18:16; 2 Corinthians 13:1; 1 Timothy 5:19). The requirement that witnesses cast the first stone (17:7) is not merely procedural; it is morally transformative. Those who testify against a person bear responsibility for the consequence of their testimony. They cannot remain at a distance from the judgment they have initiated. This accountability mechanism deters false accusation and binds the community's words to its actions. The purge formula that closes the unit — 'so you shall purge the evil from your midst' — frames covenant holiness as an active communal project, not a passive aspiration."
