          "title": "The law of the king — Deuteronomy's most surprising legislation",
          "body": "The royal law of verses 14–20 is the most theologically striking pericope in the chapter. Moses anticipates the monarchy before a single king has reigned, and he subordinates it to the Torah from the outset. Three prohibitions target the three sources of royal self-sufficiency: horses (military power), wives (political alliance and erotic entanglement), and silver and gold (wealth). The accumulation of each diverts the king's trust from the LORD toward created resources. Every subsequent Israelite king is measured against this text: Solomon multiplied horses, wives, silver, and gold in spectacular violation of all three prohibitions (1 Kings 10:14–11:8), and the result was exactly what Moses predicted — his heart turned away (17:17; cf. 1 Kings 11:4). The positive command — write a personal copy of the Torah in the priests' presence and read it all the days of his life (17:18–19) — is the antidote. The king's character is not formed by conquest or court ceremony but by daily, lifelong engagement with the Word. The expected outcome is a heart that is not lifted up above his brothers (17:20) — a king who leads not from entitlement but from covenantal solidarity with the people he governs."
